  "prompt": "Is it normal to have a dark ring around the iris of my eye?",
  "response": "Yes, having a dark ring around the iris of your eye can be normal and is often a natural variation in eye color. This ring is sometimes referred to as a **limbal ring**, which is a dark circle that separates the iris from the white part of the eye (the sclera). Limbal rings are more common in younger individuals and can become less prominent with age.\n\n### When to Be Concerned:\nWhile it\u2019s usually harmless, there are some situations where a dark ring around the iris might warrant attention:\n1. **Sudden Appearance**: If the ring appears suddenly or changes significantly, it could be a sign of an underlying condition.\n2. **Accompanying Symptoms**: If you notice other symptoms like pain, vision changes, redness, or swelling, it\u2019s a good idea to consult an eye doctor (ophthalmologist).\n3. **Discoloration**: If the ring is very dark or irregular, it could be related to conditions like **corneal arcus** (a cholesterol deposit) or **pigmentation changes**, which might need evaluation.\n\n### Common Causes:\n- **Genetics**: Some people naturally have more prominent limbal rings.\n- **Aging**: Limbal rings often fade as you get older.\n- **Eye Conditions**: Rarely, conditions like **Fuchs' heterochromic iridocyclitis** can cause changes in iris pigmentation.\n\nIf you\u2019re unsure or concerned, it\u2019s always best to consult an eye care professional for a proper evaluation.",
